<subSubSection id="4FD45EF308CBC4175DAE4B13350E5AE1" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="959679249DE7C183DCCE900C25DF4ED1" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="642A1A365F038AD43FA55492B88B11F0" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Mountain cliff ledges and rocks, in rocky ravines and on riversides. It mostly occurs out of the reach of large herbivores such as deer or sheep as, like most leafy hawkweeds, is likely to be selectively eaten. The altitudes range from 130-414 m. It flowers from late July to August, and is probably apomictic. Some plants may produce sparse pollen and others none (
<bibRefCitation id="7C38D595AFCD646DE1FB054AE721F0F0" author="Thomas, S" journalOrPublisher="Edinburgh Journal of Botany" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refId="B11" refString="Thomas, S, Bailey, J, Rich, TCG, in press. Pollen and cytological studies in Hieracium section Alpestria (Asteraceae). In: Nordic Journal of Botany." title="Pollen and cytological studies in Hieracium section Alpestria (Asteraceae)" volumeTitle="Nordic Journal of Botany." year="in press">Thomas et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A39BC4970C6D21D1779C6F40286D9659" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis id="CA616B066A7078BEF66FA5E7F57E9BF0" bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Etymology</emphasis>
. The epithet honours David J. McCosh for his work in mapping British and Irish 
<taxonomicName id="FB19995946FDFA47C8DE862867EE1F3A" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Asteraceae" genus="Hieracium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Campanulales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9456EB2D52A76B274E179B86031C7CFA" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Hieracium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa over the last 30 years, and for mentoring me. The spelling 
<normalizedToken id="CC555B657339FFC190FDBF6E770D9104" originalValue="‘maccoshiana’">
' 
<emphasis id="FB3B5D03EB3D599264F40E0125466AE2" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">maccoshiana</emphasis>
</normalizedToken>
' follows recommendation 60C.5.a of the International Code of Botanical Nomenclature (Vienna Code McNeil et al. 2006).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="63085BAA4F3414D5E8A483391A75FDB2" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis id="1A9438DBDDADDC237DDC673B29D25A59" bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Conservation status</emphasis>
. Surveys in 2010 revealed about 60 plants in four sites (see supplementary file 1: 
<taxonomicName id="93E17D0F7941489028D0A9970481C641" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Asteraceae" genus="Hieracium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Campanulales" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="dovrense">
<emphasis id="36708577C4A985B642A6D6B6B28D3AF0" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Hieracium dovrense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
survey 2010). It is thus best considered at 
<bibRefCitation id="CFD530D678E0CE3F522E3D53874744FD" author="IUCN," journalOrPublisher="International Union for Conservation of Nature, Gland" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refId="B2" refString="IUCN, , 2001. IUCN Red List Categories. Version 3.1. International Union for Conservation of Nature, Gland" title="IUCN Red List Categories. Version 3.1." year="2001">IUCN (2001)</bibRefCitation>
threat status 
<normalizedToken id="31C63537908B4385028D3173C19AEAAA" originalValue="‘Endangered’">'Endangered'</normalizedToken>
due to the small population size.
</paragraph>
